<TEXT>
rockwell international corp and two former 
managers pleaded innocent monday to charges that they overbilled 
the air force by 450000 on a sophisticated satellite navigational 
system 
in a brief hearing us district judge consuelo marshall 
ordered the company and its former managers to file pretrial 
motions by april 4 and set a may 3 trial date rockwell spokesman 
jeff charney said 
he indicated the company plans to make pretrial motions but 
declined to elaborate 
the company and the former managers donald carter materials 
division director at the its seal beach plant and robert 
zavodnick manager of major subcontracts within the division were 
named in a 25count federal indictment in january 
the indictment alleged that the company and two men 
doublebilled the government for work on the navstar global 
navigational system that uses radio signals from satellites to 
pinpoint locations on earth 
as a result the indictment claimed rockwell received 450000 
in unlawful profits 
the company has denied the allegations 
</TEXT>
