<TEXT>
hungarian intellectuals and a member of 
parliament have called on hungary to allow more ethnic hungarian 
refugees to emigrate from romania and appealed for international 
support in monitoring their rights 
about 20 people spoke at the allday forum sunday in a theater 
in budapest more than 700 people attended the meeting 
participants informed the associated press by telephone from the 
hungarian capital 
the meeting sunday was the second one of the democratic 
forum since the group was formed on sept 27 in southern hungary 
the document issued at the september meeting called for genuinely 
effective reform to resolve hungarys economic and social 
problems 
the meetings are unusual in communist hungary because 
authorities although they have not officially recognized the 
forum have not prevented them from taking place and the results 
have been discussed in the official press 
most of the speakers sunday focused on the ethnic hungarian 
minority in romania 
hungary and romania are warsaw pact allies but have engaged in 
increasingly sharp rhetoric over the question of the ethnic 
hungarian minority in transylvania in recent months 
transylvania was ruled by hungary before world war i and both 
nations claim the area is the cradle of their national cultures and 
history 
hungarian officials say increasing numbers of romanias nearly 2 
million ethnic hungarians have sought refuge in hungary 
geza szoecs an ethnic hungarian poet from transylvania who now 
lives in switzerland suggested that the hungarian government 
consider allowing a certain quota of ethnic hungarians from romania 
emigrate to hungary 
he suggested the quota correlate to the number of hungarians who 
apply for asylum in the west each year as well as the general 
decline of the population through the sinking birthrate 
however zoltan kiraly a member of parliament warned against 
establishing a refugee program that would help romanian communist 
leader nicolae ceausescu get rid of the hungarian minority 
ethnic hungarians have said they are increasingly restricted in 
the use of their language and expression of their culture in 
romania which denies the charges and accuses budapest of meddling 
in its affairs 
kiraly told the gathering he and five other parliamentarians 
drafted a resolution calling on the government to set up a 
settlement fund for transylvanian hungarians who wish to stay in 
hungary 
he said the draft resolution which is to be put before 
parliament when it meets in spring session later this month also 
calls on the government to seek the cooperation of the united 
nations and the international red cross and to mobilize 
international public opinion 
kiraly one of the most outspoken members of parliament said 
many hungarians who enter hungary from romania go on to third 
countries because the hungarian authorities are not prepared to 
receive them 
he said many of these ethnic hungarians if given the chance 
would opt to stay in hungary because of the cultural affinity 
