unsponsored afghanistan peace talks resumed 
today with uncertainty persisting over whether pakistan is ready to 
sign an agreement with the sovietbacked kabul government which it 
does not recognize 
resumption of talks came after unprecedented consultations 
between the pakistani government and opposition leaders attended by 
islamabads chief negotiator acting foreign minister zain noorani 
sources close to the meetings held during the weekend in 
pakistan said most of 19 opposition parties urged the government 
not to stand in the way of the proposed pullout of the estimated 
115000 soviet troops helping kabul to fight moslem insurgents 
soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev has said a withdrawal could 
start in midmay if a settlement is signed by next week 
in an interview published today pakistani president mohammad 
zia ulhaq said his country will not budge from its demand for an 
interim government in kabul as part of a settlement 
the gulf news daily reported that zia was optimistic that the 
proposed peace accord on afghanistan will be signed on schedule 
there is no question of the accord not going through allowing 
it to be dropped is no option he was quoted as saying 
upon his return to geneva sunday night noorani said the 
formation of a broadbased transitional government was as important 
as the troop withdrawl in bringing peace to the region 
why should we not insist on an interim government he said 
in response to a question from a reporter at the airport 
last week noorani said pakistan would make up its mind after the 
islamabad consultations on whether to sign a settlement with the 
present kabul government of president najib which pakistan does 
not recognize 
he put up only a cryptic smile when asked again before todays 
session if islamabad was now prepared to sign 
pakistan has insisted that any agreement on the withdrawal 
soviet troops should be linked to formation of an interim 
government that is acceptable to all sides in the 9yearold war 
the islamabad government says this is the only way to ensure the 
safe repatriation of 5 million afghan refugees from pakistan and 
iran 
pakistan has been representing afghan rebels at the 
unsponsored talks which began in 1982 
the resistance movements which say they represent 200000 
guerrillas have rejected any powersharing with afghanistans 
president najib and have presented a plan of their own for an 
islamic government 
the afghan government says its own policy of national 
reconciliation envisages a coalition government open to all 
political forces including the pakistanbased resistance movements 
the soviet union which sent its troops in december 1979 to help 
a faltering marxist government suppress a moslem insurrection no 
longer demands a transitional government be formed before 
withdrawal 
diego cordovez the un undersecretary general who has been 
mediating the afghan talks said last week all major differences 
had been resolved in the first three days of the new negotiating 
round which began last wednesday 
the two sides agreed on a ninemonth timetable for the 
withdrawal of soviet troops from afghanistan cordovez said this 
agreement following years of stalling on the timetable issue 
represented a significant step toward a final political 
settlement 
the sides also agreed that half of the soviet troops would leave 
in the first threemonth phase the socalled frontend loading 
which had been a major concern of the united states 
