the supreme court today cleared the way for a 
trial in what may become an important test case on the power of 
cities to control rents and otherwise protect mobile home residents 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by santa barbara 
calif officials aimed at killing a lawsuit by the owners of a 
mobile home park who claim they unfairly are being deprived of 
their propertys full value 
a santa barbara ordinance adopted in 1984 requires mobile home 
park operators to offer their tenants leases of unlimited duration 
it also permits a maximum yearly rent increase of 3 percent or 
threefourths of the increase in the consumer price index 
whichever is greater 
the ordinance was challenged by william and jean hall who own 
the los amigos mobile home estates in santa barbara 
they said their property is being taken without the just 
compensation required by the constitution 
the halls argued that granting mobile home owners a perpetual 
lease allows them to sell the lease at a windfall profit the 
windfall is due to the new owners anticipation of continued low 
land rent at belowmarket rates the halls said 
a federal judge threw out the suit but the 9th us circuit 
court of appeals reinstated it in 1986 
the appeals court noted that the halls said the price of mobile 
homes in the park shot up dramatically after the ordinance was 
enacted suggesting the guaranteed low rents were worth a premium 
to buyers 
reduced to its essentials the appeals court said the 
halls claim is that the santa barbara ordinance has transferred 
a possessory interest in their land to each of their 71 tenants 
this interest consists of the right to occupy the property in 
perpetuity while paying only a fraction of what it is worth in 
rent 
the appeals court acknowledged that the ordinance allows mobile 
home owners to be removed if they dont pay the rent or if they 
misbehave that may ease the economic impact the appeals court 
said but it does not alter the basic right of possession given the 
home owners 
the ordinance changes the fundamental relationship between the 
parties giving landlord and tenant complementary estates in the 
same land the appeals court said 
the appeals court said a trial is necessary to determine if the 
halls allegations about a windfall are accurate 
santa barbara county and other cities in california joined in 
asking the high court to review the case the cities are berkeley 
capitola carson cathedral city fontana hayward los altos los 
angeles mountain view oxnard palm springs rancho mirage 
rialto san buenaventura san jose san luis obispo santa monica 
vacaville vallejo west hollywood and westlake village 
the justices on feb 24 expanded the power of communities to 
impose rent controls by upholding a san jose calif ordinance 
that allows hardships to tenants to be considered when landlords 
seek rent increases 
the ordinance had been atttacked as a robin hood law that 
steals from the rich to pay the poor 
the case is santa barbara vs hall 87220 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

