<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to allow an 
indian tribe to withhold from federal officials confidential 
records of a tribal court proceeding 
the justices without comment let stand a ruling that gave the 
government custody of court records of the red lake band of 
chippewa indians in minnesota 
the tribe in 1985 declared that records of proceedings before 
its court of indian offenses are confidential and not the federal 
governments property 
the chippewas were concerned that if the documents were given to 
the interior departments bureau of indian affairs the agency 
would be forced to surrender the material to a newspaper that 
sought the records under the freedom of information act foia 
indian tribes are not covered by the foia and may not be forced 
directly to reveal confidential information to the news media 
the 8th us circuit court of appeals ruled last august that the 
bureau of indian affairs is entitled to the material 
the appeals court rejected arguments by the red lake band that 
only congress could grant the government access to the records and 
ruled that the government has sovereignty over tribal courts 
despite the absence of specific congressional authorization 
the considerable independence given tribes to govern themselves 
does not mean they have the power automatically to withhold 
information from the government the appeals court said 
the red lake band court of indian offenses was established in 
1884 under authority granted to the tribe by federal officials 
the 8th circuit court said that if the chippewa court had been 
created under a later federal statute the indian reorganization 
act of 1934 the confidential records might be exempt from federal 
control 
the case is red lake band vs us 87950 
