<TEXT>
two noted sex experts who criticized health 
authorities for failing to stress the extent of the aids epidemic 
said today that their own estimates of the spread of aids were 
based on beliefs and estimates not scientific evidence 
we did not project our own database on to the general 
population said robert kolodny coauthor with william masters 
and virginia johnson of crisis heterosexual behavior in the age 
of aids 
kolodny said at a press conference this morning that the 
authors assertion that aids is now running rampant in the 
heterosexual community was an estimate based on analysis of 
existing studies that have appeared in scientific journals it was 
not based on original research by the authors he said 
masters asked for his justification of the claim said i 
simply believe it 
the authors criticized health authorities for failing to stress 
the threat of aids to heterosexuals and they have themselves been 
criticized by an aids expert for making recommendations that might 
alarm the public 
but in their book masters johnson and kolodny say that medical 
experts have played down their findings rather than present 
worstcase scenarios in the understandable wish to avoid mass 
panic 
the book calls for widespread mandatory testing for acquired 
immune deficiency syndrome infection by pregnant women couples 
seeking marriage licenses and hospital patients between ages 15 and 
60 
excerpts from the book are appearing in this weeks issue of 
newsweek magazine the authors run the masters and johnson 
institute in st louis and wrote a bestseller human sexual 
response 
but some aids experts questioned their conclusions on the spread 
of the deadly disease 
masters and johnson may have expertise in sexuality but they 
have no credentials to justify their recommendations concerning 
aids public health policy recommendations that will surely alarm 
the public said mathilde krim founding chairwoman of the 
american foundation for aids research 
from everything we know today such mandatory testing schemes 
will not help protect the public she said saturday 
masters and johnsons book suggests that to guard against 
infection potential sexual partners undergo tests and remain 
monogamous 
dr beny j primm a member of president reagans aids 
commission said he agreed that recent optimistic reports about 
heterosexuals could lull people into a state of complacency 
he said as a result many dont use condoms still are 
promiscuous and still participate in group sex or other dangerous 
activities 
the book disputed estimates that there are now about 15 million 
people infected with the virus in the united states 
it is quite likely that there are now 3 million or more 
carriers of the aids virus in the united states most of whom are 
otherwise healthy and unaware of their infected contagious 
state it said 
experts generally are gravely underestimating the degree to 
which the aids virus has spread into the heterosexual community 
it said 
the authors said they based their findings on their own study of 
800 sexually active heterosexual adults between the ages of 21 and 
40 who met three criteria no blood transfusions received since 
1977 no use of illicit drugs by injection no homosexual or 
bisexual contact since 1977 
the study however did not appear to follow the usual 
scientific process and the authors conceded that their sample was 
not obtained by random sampling methods and did not closely match 
the general us population 
they said they found that among a subgroup of subjects who 
average more than 12 partners annually and generally failed to take 
precautions 14 percent of the women had been infected with the 
aids virus and 12 percent of the men 
the findings were an indication the researchers said that 
public health authorities have failed to impress the general 
public with the message that aids has broken out 
