<TEXT>
americans took out 542 billion more in 
installment debt than they paid off in january the biggest monthly 
increase in four months and the second strong month in a row the 
government said monday 
the federal reserve said consumer credit grew at a seasonally 
adjusted rate of 106 percent in january following an increase of 
398 billion in december which translated to an annual rate of 
79 percent 
growth in both months was greater than the 59 percent rate for 
all of 1987 which represents a considerable slowdown compared with 
recent years the rate was 105 percent in 1986 
the relatively strong january report is both a reflection of job 
growth unemployment hit a nineyear low of 57 percent in 
february and a sign that the rebound in consumer confidence after 
the october stock market crash is continuing according to david 
cross an economist with the futures group a washington consulting 
firm 
what were seeing right now is a sort of soft landing for 
consumer spending said cross whose firm is predicting growth 
between 65 percent and 7 percent this year were not really 
looking for a recession to occur if anything just a bit of 
slowness in the first half of the year 
the january increase was the biggest advance since debt rose by 
643 billion in september the gains in both months were strongly 
influenced by an upturn in car sales 
auto loans rose by 154 billion in january an annual rate of 
71 percent and followed a stronger gain of 107 percent in 
december 
credit card and revolving loans grew by 20 billion in january 
a 165 percent annual rate following an increase of 193 percent a 
month earlier 
the debt category which includes bank and credit union loans not 
secured by real estate grew by 173 billion an 116 percent 
growth rate following a decline of 35 percent in december 
loans for mobile homes increased 142 million after falling 122 
million in december 
the various changes left total consumer debt at 6175 billion 
in january 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

