<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday set the stage for 
an important ruling on sex discrimination agreeing to study a case 
in which unconscious stereotyping allegedly played a key role 
in denying a woman an accounting firm partnership 
the justices said they will review a ruling that places a heavy 
burden on employers to disprove sex bias 
arguments in the case will be heard in the fall during the 
courts next term and a decision is not likely to be announced 
until 1989 
price waterhouse one of the nations largest accounting firms 
is accused of discriminating unlawfully against ann hopkins she 
quit the firms office here after she was denied promotion to 
partnership a move that would have made her a part owner 
ms hopkins joined the firm in 1978 and was nominated for 
partnership in 1982 the only woman among 88 candidates for 
partnership that year 
she had been very successful in getting business for the 
company winning government contracts worth an estimated 34 
million to 44 million 
of the 88 candidates 47 were invited to become partners 21 
were rejected outright and 20 including ms hopkins were placed on 
hold 
the following year she was told she would not become a partner 
and she resigned in 1984 to set up her own consulting firm 
both her critics and supporters at price waterhouse said she 
sometimes was overly aggressive too harsh impatient with her 
staff and very demanding 
one critic suggested she needed to take a course at charm 
school 
a partner in the firm who urged her promotion told her she would 
stand a better chance of becoming a partner if she would walk 
more femininely talk more femininely dress more femininely wear 
makeup have her hair styled and wear jewelry 
others said her use of profanity was a black mark against her 
ms hopkins then sued price waterhouse accusing the company of 
violating title vii of the 1964 civil rights act prohibiting 
onthejob sex disscrimination she said that sex stereotyping 
unconscious or otherwise barred her from being named partner 
the supreme court ruled in 1984 in the case of a woman denied 
partnership in a law firm that professional partnerships are 
covered by the 1964 law 
a federal judge ruled price waterhouse must prove by clear and 
convincing evidence it would not have made her a partner 
regardless of whether sexual stereotyping played a part in its 
decision 
price waterhouse said it was unable to provide such proof 
the us circuit court of appeals here last august said there is 
competent evidence that the partnership selection process at 
price waterhouse was impermissibly infected by stereotypical 
attitudes toward female candidates 
the appeals court said even if there is evidence that ms 
hopkins personality played a part in her denial of partnership 
price waterhouse is unable to prove impermissible bias was not 
the determinative factor 
the appeals court ordered further hearings to determine what 
back pay and other remedies the company must provide 
the case is price waterhouse vs hopkins 871167 
