routine strip searches of children awaiting 
deportation are unconstitutional a federal judge ruled monday 
saying immigration agents must first have a reasonable suspicion 
that drugs or weapons have been hidden 
us district judge robert kelleher rejected an immigration and 
naturalization service argument that the bodycavity searches are 
needed because adults will use children as couriers if agents 
cannot search them 
children confined by the ins are not charged with any criminal 
offense let alone an offense that might indicate a propensity to 
conceal weapons or contraband on their persons kelleher ruled 
in 1987 of 84000 aliens searched there were 20 discoveries of 
contraband or weapons only four of which were related to 
juveniles kelleher noted 
his ruling came in a classaction suit filed in 1985 by a 
coalition of immigrants rights groups that challenged what they 
described as routine stripsearches of children upon admission to 
ins detention facilities and following all visits with anyone other 
than attorneys 
