<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday postponed until 
later in the year a ruling in a multibilliondollar battle over 
socalled gray market goods the growing business that allows 
consumers to purchase costly imports at steep discounts 
the justices announced they again will hear arguments in the 
case in april with a decision expected by july 
the case will be reargued with justice anthony m kennedy who 
joined the court last month taking part in the deliberations 
kennedys participation in the case will give the court six 
members a quorum to consider the underlying dispute 
kennedy did not take part as the court ruled 53 on monday 
that the court of international trade does not have exclusive 
authority over the dispute the majority said that a federal judge 
properly considered the case 
the three justices who dissented did so on a procedural issue 
they said the federal courts lacked jurisdiction a decision that 
would in effect disqualify them from considering the merits of the 
case 
the dispute is over interpretation of the federal tariff act of 
1930 the us customs service says the law allows gray market 
goods into the country without approval from trademark owners 
two leading discount distributors k mart corp and 47th street 
photo inc of new york city also are defending the customs service 
regulations 
typically the discount companies buy trademarked products in 
the united states more cheaply than do the owners of the us 
trademarks 
some 60 major companies that own trademarks banded together to 
form the coalition to preserve the integrity of american trademarks 
and challenge the customs service regulations 
a federal judge upheld the customs service regulations but the 
us circuit court of appeals here ruled last year that the rules 
are invalid under the 1930 tariff act 
the statute prohibits unauthorized imports of any merchandise 
of foreign manufacture if such merchandise bears a trademark 
owned by a citizen of or by a corporation or association created 
or organized within the united states 
the customs service says the law protects only american 
companies that purchase trademarks from independent foreign 
manufacturers and does not protect american subsidiaries 
affiliates or parent companies of foreign manufacturers 
justice william j brennan wrote mondays opinion upholding the 
authority of the federal courts to rule in the dispute he was 
joined by justices byron r white thurgood marshall harry a 
blackmun and john paul stevens 
dissenting on the jurisdictional issue were chief justice 
william h rehnquist and justices antonin scalia and sandra day 
oconnor 
</TEXT>
