<TEXT>
secretary of state george p shultz met monday 
with chinese foreign minister wu xueqian and said the united states 
is prepared to increase high technology exports to china 
during toasts following their state department luncheon the two 
leaders hailed the progress in bilateral relations and made almost 
no reference to issues which divide them 
chief among them is chinas reported sales of military weaponry 
to iran in defiance of us efforts at the united nations to win 
support for a worldwide arms embargo against iran the 
administration has been seeking assurances from china that it will 
not veto an embargo resolution 
the reagan administration has generally refrained from public 
condemnations of the chinese sales and shultz on monday alluded 
only to press reports in both countries of uschinese 
differences on the persian gulf war 
administration officials have indicated a willingness to 
increase high technology exports to china in exchange for a chinese 
commitment to halt delivery of weapons to iran 
although shultz made no direct link between the two issues he 
indicated us interest in increasing sales of sophisticated 
technology to china 
over the last five years the united states has significantly 
liberalized its controls over technology exports to china and we 
are prepared to do more to ensure us exporters remain competitive 
in the china market he said 
last october the united states retaliated against china for 
selling silkworm antiship missiles to iran by suspending the 
process under which china had been given increasing access to us 
products with advanced technology 
since then china has said it has stopped selling silkworms to 
iran a us official speaking friday on condition of anonymity 
said our information is that theyve been living up to that 
still before resuming liberalization of the high technology 
trade we want to be sure were in sync with the chinese on what 
were talking about the official said we believe the chinese 
position has been responsive to our concerns but we want to be 
sure that this responsiveness will continue 
although no details of their private talks were disclosed 
shultz also was expected to discuss with wu the us proposal for 
direct arabisraeli peace talks 
us officials who asked not to be identified said shultzs 
talks with wu were cordial and covered a range of international 
issues 
they said discussions later in the week will focus on human 
rights and the persian gulf situation 
shultz is trying to structure a peace conference in which the 
united states the soviet union china britain and france would 
serve as sponsors but without the power to impose the terms of a 
settlement 
shultz made no reference in his remarks to recent antichinese 
rioting in tibet state department spokesman charles redman said 
between three and nine people are believed to have been killed and 
he expressed deep concern over the human rights situation in tibet 
he also reiterated the us view that tibet is an integral part 
of china 
shultz discussing shared interests of the two countries said 
both have opposed the soviet occupation of afghanistan and the 
vietnamese military intervention in cambodia 
the united states is convinced that a secure china is in the 
interest not only of china but of the us and the states of the 
east asian region shultz said 
wu in turn said there is great potential for continued 
development of uschinese relations yet there are also 
obstacles and difficulties 
therefore our two sides have no reason to rest content with 
the present status he said 
wu also met with defense secretary frank c carlucci on monday 
he will meet with president reagan on tuesday 
</TEXT>
