<TEXT>
a federal judge on monday cleared the way for 
the regional bell telephone companies to offer certain new 
computerized information services including voice storage and 
electronic mail 
but us district judge harold greene in a 66page decision 
refused to retreat from an earlier decision in which he said phone 
companies could transmit information but could not generate or 
manipulate the content of the information 
it is the courts expectation that this easing of the 
information services restriction will avoid anticompetitive 
effects and that it will at the same time bring this nation closer 
to the enjoyment of the full benefits of the information age 
greene said in his decision 
though greenes decision lifts the legal barrier to the bell 
companies offering of the new services the companies still would 
need state and federal regulatory approval before they could 
integrate them into their networks 
industry experts and bell company officials say the computer 
software for these services has been developed and could be offered 
to consumers in some parts of the country within one to two years 
voice storage and retrieval services would allow consumers to 
rely on the phone network for storing and retrieving messages 
functions now performed by telephone answering machines electronic 
mail a service now available in many private phone systems allows 
the computertocomputer transfer of messages 
in addition greene said the bell companies can perform certain 
computerized gateway services such as data transmission 
billing management and services that enable different computers to 
speak to each other 
bellsouth and bell atlantic said the decision was an important 
step toward making a wide range of information services available 
to american consumers but both said the judge did not go far 
enough and bell atlantic said it will appeal the decision 
we view this as a start but only a start we still are not 
allowed to provide content for information services a bellsouth 
statement said 
bell atlantic chairman thomas e bolger said the company is 
particularly concerned that greene is continuing to forbid the 
bell companies from electronic publishing of yellow page phone 
directories greenes september ruling allowed electronic white 
pages but bolger said the courts restrictions do not allow a 
sufficiently flexible and comprehensive electronic service for 
white pages directory 
he also said greenes decision to continue to forbid the bell 
companies from getting into the content side of information 
services will delay the delivery of more sophisticated services 
like home banking and shopping to most american consumers 
joel gross a telephone analyst with donaldson lufkin amp 
jenrette said the decision was a major breakthrough for the 
regional phone companies he said that in the long term it will 
be a tremendous boon to the industry though in the shortterm 
will have little effect on the companies earninings 
services like this since they are softwarebased should be 
highprofit services and voice storage and retrieval will create 
new traffic volumes for the phone networks he said 
gene kimmelman a spokesman for the consumer federation of 
america said the decision means regulation of the industry will 
become more important to prevent the bell companies from 
overpricing local phone service to finance these new services 
greene who oversees the antitrust decree that broke up the 
american telephone amp telegraph co four years ago has been 
reluctant to allow atampts offspring the bell companies to compete 
in areas where their control of the local phone networks would put 
them at an advantage over competitors 
last september he refused to lift prohibitions on the baby 
bells that prevent them from making phone equipment or offering 
longdistance services in considering the restrictions on 
information services however he opened the door slightly 
mondays ruling details the informationservices options now open 
to the bell companies 
