<TEXT>
the judicial misconduct hearing of a former 
vermont supreme court justice began with a delay monday as 
attorneys for a key figure in the case argued she should not have 
to testify 
attorneys for former chittenden county assistant judge jane 
wheel told the judicial conduct board that her criminal case would 
be damaged if she testified in the separate case of her friend and 
former coworker justice william hill 
hill was one of three supreme court justices accused of allowing 
their personal relationships with wheel to interfere with their 
judicial duties 
the charges filed in january 1987 by the state judicial conduct 
board named hill thomas hayes and ernest gibson iii hill has 
retired since the charges were filed hayes has died and the 
charges against gibson were dropped and he remains on the court 
the scandal threw the states highest court into turmoil the 
justices refused gov madeleine kunins request that they step 
aside but they did disqualify themselves from all cases involving 
people connected with the case 
the complaint alleged that the three used their clout to help 
wheel whether it was in minor matters like writing memos 
endorsing suggestions she made or major matters like advising her 
while she was under criminal investigation by the state attorney 
generals office for allegedly padding her paycheck 
wheel was convicted on three counts of false swearing during a 
jury trial last month she was accused of lying during an inquest 
into allegations that she submitted false pay vouchers 
wheel appeared in court briefly monday but she left after she 
and her attorneys were given one day to submit memoranda on why she 
shouldnt have to testify 
hills attorney michael marks had said he and his client 
welcomed the misconduct hearing calling it hills opportunity to 
defend himself publicly 
but most of the first days testimony centered on wheel and her 
activities as an assistant judge 
in hills written responses to the boards original charges he 
said his relationship with wheel was strictly professional and did 
not go beyond the amicable relationship expected of judges who 
work together 
but the state on monday attempted to depict a much closer 
relationship between the two 
court reporter joan giard described a gathering she attended at 
the holiday inn in waterbury wheel arrived with hill on one arm 
and hayes on the other 
she danced with justice hill that evening giard said i 
remember looking over 
marks objected to much of the testimony about wheel and her 
criminal case but was overruled by harvey otterman the chairman 
of the threemember hearing panel 
the retirement of hill 60 from the high court leaves few 
options for punishment if he is found guilty of judicial 
misconduct he could be reprimanded or perhaps restricted from 
serving on the court under a law that allows retired justices to 
sit on certain cases 
