the federal government insisted monday 
that west germany had had no serious disagreements with its nato 
allies about disarmament at an alliance summit last week 
attempts to fabricate disagreements on basic questions 
between the federal republic and its allies find a basis 
neither in the proceedings nor in the results of the summit said 
a communique 
it said chancellor helmut kohl determined at the north atlantic 
treaty organization summit in brussels belgium that the alliance 
will concentrate on working out a comprehensive disarmament 
concept 
kohl assumed from the talks that work within the alliance will 
proceed smoothly and be finished at the latest within a year 
said the statement read to reporters by government spokesman 
friedhelm ost 
it also said there should not be attempts to artifically 
create pressures on nato to make a quick decision on the 
modernization of shortrange nuclear weapons 
that remark appeared to be aimed at prime minister margaret 
thatcher of britain who told the summit that the alliance would 
soon have to think seriously about modernizing its aging 
shortrange nuclear weapons 
kohl had resisted demands at the summit for a stronger nato 
position on the modernization of shortrange nuclear weapons which 
have a range of up to 300 miles 
kohl wants nato to postpone the scheduled modernization of those 
weapons and to begin negotiations with the sovietled warsaw pact 
alliance on reducing shortrange nuclear arsenals 
mondays statement repeated kohls position that he does not 
favor total removal of nuclear weapons from europe but wants a 
reduction and parity in conventional and nuclear arms by both nato 
and the warsaw pact 
bonn officials have said west germany would be the main 
battleground in a european war because it borders east germany and 
czechoslovakia 
