<DOCNO> AP880307-0238 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to hear a 
reagan administration appeal aimed at allowing the government to 
take a bigger tax bite out of some corporate mergers 
the court said it will review a ruling stemming from the 
acquisition of a small west virginia company by a corporation 
traded on the new york stock exchange 
the smaller company basin surveys inc was owned by donald e 
clark of buckhannon wva it provides services to the petroleum 
industry 
clark sold the business in 1979 to nl industries of new york 
which produces petroleum equipment chemicals and metals 
nl industries gave clark 300000 shares of its stock and 325 
million to acquire basin surveys 
at issue in the case was whether the cash payment commonly 
called boot should be taxed as a capital gain or considered a 
dividend and taxed as ordinary income generally the capital gain 
tax rate is lower 
the tax reform bill enacted in 1986 eliminated the different tax 
rates for capital gains and ordinary income 
but the administration said the different treatment will still 
apply to some corporate shareholders 
also in urging the court to consider the government appeal 
justice department lawyers said congress sometime in the future 
might restore for all taxpayers the different treatment of ordinary 
income and capital gains 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals ruled in favor of clark 
last september sparing him from paying 972505 in taxes 
the appeals court said we regard the boot as a cash payment 
by nl in return for clarks relinquishment of a portion of his 
interest in the newly reorganized corporation because clark 
surrendered more than 20 percent of his interest in nl he is 
entitled to capital gain treatment 
the appeals court arrived at the 20 percent figure by noting 
that nl industries offere clark two choices in the merger he 
could receive either 425000 shares of nl stock or 300000 shares 
plus 325 million in cash 
the appeals court said clark by choosing the latter option in 
effect gave up more than 20 percent of his interest in nl 
industries in return for the cash 
the appeals court said that under federal law a shareholder who 
relinquishes more than 20 percent of his corporate control and is 
less than a 50 percent shareholder after the transaction is 
entitled to have cash proceeds from the transaction treated as 
capital gains 
justice department lawyers said the ruling is in conflict with 
decisions by other federal appeals courts they said the supreme 
court should eliminate the confusion 
the case is commissioner of internal revenue vs clark 871168 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
