<TEXT>
businesses that lose money from the sale of 
stock arent entitled to special tax breaks no matter why the stock 
was purchased the supreme court decided today 
the court voting 80 ruled against an arkansas conglomerate 
that sought to claim as an ordinaryloss deduction for federal tax 
purposes a 10 million loss from the sale of stock in a texas bank 
it once controlled 
arkansas best corp of fort smith in 1969 had acquired more than 
65 percent of the stock of national bank of commerce the fourth 
largest bank in dallas 
congress passed a law in 1970 that prohibited conglomerates that 
owned a bank from expanding their nonbank business through new 
acquisitions in other industries 
arkansas best which owns trucking furniture manufacturing 
data processing and other businesses decided to divest itself of 
the bank stock the 1970 law gave it 10 years to sell the bank 
stock 
because of public awareness that arkansas best was under legal 
obligation to divest itself disposing of the bank stock without 
taking a big loss was difficult 
at the same time the banks finances were deteriorating 
arkansas best therefore acquired additional stock in the bank in an 
attempt to keep it solvent 
the conglomerate began selling off the bank stock in 1975 and 
sought to claim the losses as ordinary losses rather than capital 
losses a tax advantage 
the internal revenue service ruled that the losses suffered by 
arkansas best were capital losses the irs rejected arkansas bests 
arguments that the stock was not bought for typical investment 
purposes but for business purposes and therefore its sale should 
yield ordinary losses 
the 8th us circuit court of appeals agreed with the irs but 
other federal appeals courts had reached conflicting conclusions 
writing for the high court today justice thurgood marshall said 
motivation behind the stock purchase is irrelevant to the 
question whether the asset is property held by a taxpayer and 
is thus within federal tax laws general definition of capital 
asset 
because the capital stock held by arkansas best falls within 
the broad definition of the term capital asset in the tax code 
and is outside the classes of property excluded from capitalasset 
status the loss arising from the sale of the stock is a capital 
loss marshall said 
justice anthony m kennedy did not participate in the decision 
the case is arkansas best vs commissioner of internal revenue 
86751 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

