sir nicholas goodison said monday he is resigning 
at the end of the year as chairman of the london stock exchange 
which he piloted through its big bang computer revolution in 
1986 and the market crash last october 
goodison 53 will take over the chairmanship of the trustee 
savings bank next jan 1 
i have served on the stock exchange council for the past 20 
years and been chairman for the past 12 i have been chairman 
during a period of great innovation and change and now feel that 
the structure for the future has been built goodison said in a 
statement 
an election among the stock exchanges members for a new 
chairman is likely in the fall 
goodison in his new post succeeds sir john read who will be 70 
on march 29 and due for retirement this year from leadership of the 
trustee savings bank which is a financial services group as well 
as a bank with 19 million investors 
goodison has been chairman of stockbrokers quilter goodison co 
ltd since 1975 
he said the stock crash of last october and november had nothing 
to do with his move and that the oldstyle exchange could not have 
absorbed the wave of selling 
when he became chairman goodison was confronted with the then 
labor governments decision to reconstruct the stock exchange by 
separating marketmakers and brokers into different partnerships 
eleven years later came the big bang on oct 27 1986 ending 
fixed commissions and the distinction between brokers who were 
agents in the buying and selling of shares and stockjobbers who 
actively traded in shares at prices they quoted to brokers 
