the teamsters union asked northwest airlines on 
monday to submit issues separating the company and its 6500 flight 
attendants to binding arbitration 
northwest airlines said it would not agree to arbitration but 
was willing to resume talks 
william genoese director of the teamsters airline division 
said flight attendants were prepared to strike if the airline did 
not agree to arbitration in 72 hours 
gov james blanchards administration backed the arbitration 
request said state labor director betty howe who joined genoese 
in a news conference at a teamsters office in detroit 
the flight attendants more than 2000 of them based in detroit 
have worked since a feb 26 strike deadline but no talks have been 
held for the past week 
genoese cited economic and safety concerns as reasons for 
holding off on a strike this long 
he referred to a federal aviation administration report friday 
on safety concerns at northwest airlines and said a strike would 
mean operating with less experienced replacement flight attendants 
this would threaten both the comfort and safety of northwest 
passengers he said 
issues dividing the two sides include a twotier wage system 
under which attendants hired after may 1984 must work five years to 
earn the same as those hired earlier the airline proposes to 
extend the time to nine years 
howe without commenting on the merits of either side said 
the blanchard administration is concerned about the detroitbased 
flight attendants jobs and the potential economic impact of a 
strike 
northwest airlines accounts for about half the air traffic in 
and out of detroit metropolitan airport the largest of its three 
hubs the airline operates about 248 flights a day at metro about 
227 at minneapolis where it is headquartered and 201 at its 
memphis tenn hub 
